        <h4>Nicki Clarke</h4>
        <p class="body-paragraph">Executive Director, Capitol Center for the Arts</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="home-testimonials__item">
    <p class="body-paragraph">The goals were to reflect on individual leadership as well as the school’s leadership programming. This two day conference was kicked off with an amazing speaker, Deo Mwano. He helped all the student leadership to think about equity and inclusion in leadership. He brought a key understanding to all the students about making sure all have access and who the stakeholders and decision makers are and how to partner with them. He spent time asking students to think about their leadership style and how the “show up” as leaders. The experience with Deo was overwhelmingly positive for students and set the stage on day 2 to work with the Dean of Students and Leadership, Reina Stimpson, about using their skills to build up their team within their individual student life and government groups. Students used an Affirmative Inquiry approach to speak about what was working well and what they wanted to see more of and improve.</p>
    <div class="home-testimonials__item-meta">
